5. Implementation Details
Database Design Approach

The database was designed using relational database concepts. Each module of the AI Interview System was separated into individual tables to reduce redundancy and improve maintainability.

The implementation process included:

Requirement analysis
Identification of entities
Table creation
Relationship mapping
Foreign key integration
Constraint validation
Testing and optimization
5.1 Candidate Table

This table stores candidate information.

Column Name	Data Type	Constraints
candidate_id	INT	PRIMARY KEY
name	VARCHAR(100)	NOT NULL
email	VARCHAR(100)	UNIQUE
interview_domain	VARCHAR(100)	NOT NULL
SQL Code
CREATE TABLE Candidate (
    candidate_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL,
    email VARCHAR(100) UNIQUE NOT NULL,
    interview_domain VARCHAR(100) NOT NULL
);
5.2 Monitoring Logs Table

This table stores monitoring violations detected during interviews.

Column Name	Data Type	Constraints
log_id	INT	PRIMARY KEY
candidate_id	INT	FOREIGN KEY
timestamp	TIMESTAMP	DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
violation_type	VARCHAR(100)	NULL
severity	VARCHAR(50)	NULL
SQL Code
CREATE TABLE Monitoring_Logs (
    log_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    candidate_id INT NOT NULL,
    timestamp TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,
    violation_type VARCHAR(100),
    severity VARCHAR(50),


    CONSTRAINT fk_candidate_logs
        FOREIGN KEY(candidate_id)
        REFERENCES Candidate(candidate_id)
        ON DELETE CASCADE
);
5.3 Risk Score Table

This table stores AI-generated risk analysis results.

Column Name	Data Type	Constraints
score_id	INT	PRIMARY KEY
candidate_id	INT	FOREIGN KEY
risk_score	DECIMAL(5,2)	NULL
interview_status	VARCHAR(50)	NULL
SQL Code
CREATE TABLE Risk_Score (
    score_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    candidate_id INT NOT NULL,
    risk_score DECIMAL(5,2),
    interview_status VARCHAR(50),


    CONSTRAINT fk_candidate_score
        FOREIGN KEY(candidate_id)
        REFERENCES Candidate(candidate_id)
        ON DELETE CASCADE
);
5.4 Session Table

This table stores interview session information.

Column Name	Data Type	Constraints
session_id	INT	PRIMARY KEY
candidate_id	INT	FOREIGN KEY
start_time	TIMESTAMP	NULL
end_time	TIMESTAMP	NULL
SQL Code
CREATE TABLE Session (
    session_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    candidate_id INT NOT NULL,
    start_time TIMESTAMP,
    end_time TIMESTAMP,


    CONSTRAINT fk_candidate_session
        FOREIGN KEY(candidate_id)
        REFERENCES Candidate(candidate_id)
        ON DELETE CASCADE
);
5.5 Transcript Table

This table stores candidate interview transcripts.

Column Name	Data Type	Constraints
transcript_id	INT	PRIMARY KEY
session_id	INT	FOREIGN KEY
question	TEXT	NULL
answer	TEXT	NULL
timestamp	TIMESTAMP	DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
SQL Code
CREATE TABLE Transcripts (
    transcript_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    session_id INT NOT NULL,
    question TEXT,
    answer TEXT,
    timestamp TIMESTAMP DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP,


    CONSTRAINT fk_session_transcript
        FOREIGN KEY(session_id)
        REFERENCES Session(session_id)
        ON DELETE CASCADE
);
5.6 Evaluation Table

This table stores AI-generated evaluation results.

Column Name	Data Type	Constraints
evaluation_id	INT	PRIMARY KEY
session_id	INT	FOREIGN KEY
communication_score	DECIMAL(5,2)	NULL
technical_score	DECIMAL(5,2)	NULL
confidence_score	DECIMAL(5,2)	NULL
final_result	VARCHAR(50)	NULL
SQL Code
CREATE TABLE Evaluations (
    evaluation_id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    session_id INT NOT NULL,
    communication_score DECIMAL(5,2),
    technical_score DECIMAL(5,2),
    confidence_score DECIMAL(5,2),
    final_result VARCHAR(50),


    CONSTRAINT fk_session_evaluation
        FOREIGN KEY(session_id)
        REFERENCES Session(session_id)
        ON DELETE CASCADE
);
6. Database Relationships

The database follows relational design principles.

Relationships
One Candidate can have multiple Monitoring Logs.
One Candidate can have multiple Sessions.
One Session can contain multiple Transcripts.
One Session can have one Evaluation record.
Foreign keys ensure data integrity between tables.
7. Testing & Validation
Testing Performed

The following testing methods were used:

Table creation testing
Foreign key validation
Data insertion testing
Query execution testing
Relationship consistency testing
Challenges Faced
Foreign Key Constraint Error

During implementation, an incompatibility error occurred between foreign key columns because SERIAL and INT datatypes were mixed.

Solution

The issue was resolved by using consistent datatypes across all related tables:

INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY

This ensured compatibility between parent and child tables.

